# 🚀 Advanced Missing Data Management and Imputation Strategies in MATLAB

Following the initial data loading phase, this section addresses the systematic handling of incomplete datasets—a critical prerequisite for robust machine learning pipelines. Missing values can severely bias statistical analyses and degrade model performance if left unmanaged.

This module details quantitative strategies for **detecting**, **deleting**, and **imputing** missing observations using MATLAB's native statistical frameworks.

---

## 📂 Module 4.2 & 4.3: Missing Data Diagnostics and Imputation

Using the standard `carsmall` benchmark dataset, this script isolates incomplete entries, calculates feature-wise missingness patterns, and compares multiple handling strategies including listwise/pairwise deletion, measures of central tendency (mean, median, mode), and mathematical interpolation.

### 🛠️ Academic MATLAB Framework

The script below performs data restructuring, computes diagnostic metrics, and implements five distinct data recovery algorithms. All syntax, variables, and logs are implemented in technical English:

```matlab
clc;
clear;
close all;

load carsmall;                                                                                % Load standard benchmark repository dataset
data = table(MPG, Cylinders, Displacement, Horsepower, Weight, Acceleration, Model_Year, Origin,...
    'VariableNames', {'MPG', 'Cylinders', 'Displacement', 'Horsepower', 'Weight', 'Acceleration', 'Model_Year', 'Origin'}); 

disp('--- Dataset Preview (First 5 Observations) ---');
disp(head(data, 5));                                                                          % Inspect initial data distribution matrices

%% PHASE 1: Missing Data Diagnostics
missingCount = sum(ismissing(data));                                                          % Compute column-wise vector of missing elements
missingTable = table(data.Properties.VariableNames', missingCount', 'VariableNames', {...     % Build structural metadata summary table
    'Variable', 'Missing_Count'});
disp('--- Missing Data Diagnostic Metrics ---');
disp(missingTable);

%% PHASE 2: Data Elimination Strategies
% Method 1.1: Listwise Deletion (Complete-Case Analysis)
data_listwise = rmmissing(data);                                                              % Strip any row containing at least one missing feature
fprintf("After Listwise Deletion: %d rows remaining.\n", height(data_listwise));

% Method 1.2: Pairwise Deletion (Feature-Specific Exclusion)
data_pairwise = data(~ismissing(data.Horsepower), :);                                         % Eliminate rows containing missingness solely in target vector
fprintf("After Pairwise Deletion (Target: Horsepower): %d rows remaining.\n", height(data_pairwise));

%% PHASE 3: Statistical Imputation Strategies
% Method 2.1.1: Mean Imputation
data_mean = data;
meanValue = mean(data.Horsepower, 'omitnan');                                                 % Compute expected arithmetic mean ignoring NaN tokens
data_mean.Horsepower(ismissing(data_mean.Horsepower)) = meanValue;                             % Substitute missing elements with calculated mean
fprintf("Calculated Mean Value: %.2f\n", meanValue);

% Method 2.1.2: Median Imputation
data_median = data;
medianValue = median(data.Horsepower, 'omitnan');                                             % Compute central statistical median ignoring NaN tokens
data_median.Horsepower(ismissing(data_median.Horsepower)) = medianValue;                       % Replace missing values with robust median value
fprintf("Calculated Median Value: %.2f\n", medianValue);

% Method 2.1.3: Mode Imputation
data_mode = data;
modeValue = mode(data.Horsepower(~ismissing(data.Horsepower)));                               % Extract most frequent categorical/discrete element 
data_mode.Horsepower(ismissing(data_mode.Horsepower)) = modeValue;                             % Input mode value into missing records
fprintf("Calculated Mode Value: %.2f\n", modeValue);

%% PHASE 4: Mathematical Interpolation
% Method 2.2: Linear Interpolation Method
data_linear = data;
data_linear.Horsepower = fillmissing(data_linear.Horsepower, 'linear');                       % Estimate missing points linearly based on boundary values
disp("Linear interpolation successfully executed.");

