# 🚀 Machine Learning Journey with MATLAB: Comprehensive Data Preprocessing Pipeline

Welcome! This repository is dedicated to documenting an end-to-end, step-by-step practical implementation of **Machine Learning workflows within the MATLAB environment**, spanning from baseline pipeline construction to advanced statistical modeling.

In statistical learning theory, a model's predictive generalized capability is strictly bounded by the structural integrity of its training matrix—a paradigm frequently described as *"Garbage In, Garbage Out (GIGO)"*. This repository establishes a rigorous pipeline designed to systematically clean, restructure, and transform noisy raw inputs into high-fidelity data structures optimized for downstream machine learning estimators.

---

## 📂 Module 4: Advanced Data Analysis and Preprocessing Pipeline

This section encompasses three foundational pillars of the preprocessing pipeline:
1. **Module 4.1: Structural File Ingestion and Variable Localization** – Transitioning raw databanks into tabular formats.
2. **Module 4.2 & 4.3: Missing Data Diagnostics and Advanced Imputation Frameworks** – Identifying incomplete data matrices and implementing statistical recovery protocols.
3. **Module 4.4 & 4.5: Categorical Variable Encoding Frameworks** – Converting qualitative features into continuous mathematical matrices via Binary, Label, and One-Hot Encoding techniques.

### 🛠️ Integrated Academic MATLAB Framework

The following comprehensive script reads a raw dataset, runs programmatic diagnostic routines to manage missing observations (`NaN`), and executes advanced categorical encoding mechanisms suitable for standard machine learning pipelines:

```matlab
clc;
clear;
close all;

%% =========================================================================
%% STAGE 1: STRUCTURAL FILE INGESTION & RESTYLING (Module 4.1)
%% =========================================================================
% Load the standard benchmark repository dataset to simulate an ingested pipeline
load carsmall;                                                                                

% Restructure arrays into a unified statistical table matrix
dataLines = table(MPG, Cylinders, Displacement, Horsepower, Weight, Acceleration, Model_Year, Origin,...
    'VariableNames', {'MPG', 'Cylinders', 'Displacement', 'Horsepower', 'Weight', 'Acceleration', 'Model_Year', 'Origin'}); 

disp('--- Stage 1: Dataset Pipeline Ingestion Completed ---');
disp('Previewing the first 5 records of the structured matrix:');
disp(head(dataLines, 5));                                                                          

%% =========================================================================
%% STAGE 2: MISSING DATA DIAGNOSTICS & HANDLING (Module 4.2 & 4.3)
%% =========================================================================
rowCount = size(dataLines, 1);
columnCount = size(dataLines, 2);
fprintf("Ingested Matrix Dimensions: [Rows: %d, Columns: %d]\n\n", rowCount, columnCount);

missingCount = sum(ismissing(dataLines));                                                     % Compute feature-wise vector of missing elements
missingTable = table(dataLines.Properties.VariableNames', missingCount', 'VariableNames', {... % Construct metadata structural log
    'Feature_Variable', 'Missing_Observation_Count'});

disp('--- Stage 2: Missing Data Diagnostic Metrics ---');
disp(missingTable);

% Execute Mathematical Linear Interpolation to clean numeric voids
dataLines.Horsepower = fillmissing(dataLines.Horsepower, 'linear');                       
disp("Mathematical linear interpolation protocol successfully executed.");

%% =========================================================================
%% STAGE 3: CATEGORICAL DATA ENCODING MECHANISMS (Module 4.4 & 4.5)
%% =========================================================================
% Importing a sample multi-class dataset for encoding demonstrations
% data = readtable('train.csv'); % Standard ingestion call

% Synthesizing categorical types for structural encoding conversions
dataLines.Sex = categorical(dataLines.Origin);                                                % Casting character arrays to categorical classes
dataLines.Embarked = categorical(dataLines.Origin);                                           

disp(' ');
disp('--- Stage 3: Initializing Categorical Encoders ---');

% Protocol 3.1: Binary Encoding (0-1 Transformation for Dichotomous Features)
uniqueClasses = categories(dataLines.Sex);
dataLines.Sex_Binary = double(dataLines.Sex == uniqueClasses{2});                             % Assigning Boolean flags (0 or 1) based on class evaluation
disp('Previewing Binary Encoding Results (First 10 Rows):');
disp(table(dataLines.Sex(1:10), dataLines.Sex_Binary(1:10), 'VariableNames', {'Original', 'Encoded_Binary'}));

% Protocol 3.2: Label Encoding (Integer Mapping for Ordinal/Nominal Features)
[dataLines.Embarked_Label, categoryNames] = grp2idx(dataLines.Embarked);                      % Generating distinct sequential integer indices per group
encodingMapTable = table((1:numel(categoryNames))', categoryNames, 'VariableNames', {'Label_Index', 'Category'});
disp('Generated Label Encoding Index Reference Mapping:');
disp(encodingMapTable);

% Protocol 3.3: One-Hot Encoding (Dummy Variable Matrix Expansion)
uniqueCategories = categories(dataLines.Embarked);
categoryCount = numel(uniqueCategories);

for i = 1:categoryCount
    columnLabel = ['Origin_OneHot_', char(uniqueCategories{i})];                              % Generating descriptive headers dynamically
    dataLines.(columnLabel) = double(dataLines.Embarked == uniqueCategories{i});              % Vectorizing category membership into dummy columns
end
disp('Previewing Dynamically Generated One-Hot Encoded Structural Matrix Columns:');
disp(dataLines(1:10, end-categoryCount+1:end));

